WEBVTT

0
00:00:03.700 --> 00:00:06.639
We've talked about the history and we've talked about the community.

1
00:00:06.820 --> 00:00:07.289
Now,

2
00:00:07.570 --> 00:00:08.619
let's get hands on.

3
00:00:09.789 --> 00:00:13.329
This is the Openrack version 3 or ORV 3.

4
00:00:13.529 --> 00:00:17.059
It's the physical foundation of the modern AI driven data centre.

5
00:00:17.700 --> 00:00:20.059
And to understand why it's built this way,

6
00:00:20.219 --> 00:00:22.579
you have to understand the architecture of power.

7
00:00:24.340 --> 00:00:26.100
In a traditional nineteen-inch rack,

8
00:00:26.290 --> 00:00:28.569
every server had its own power supply.

9
00:00:28.860 --> 00:00:31.100
It was plugged into a giant power strip

10
00:00:31.329 --> 00:00:32.500
known as a PDU.

11
00:00:33.340 --> 00:00:36.919
Early open racks solved this cable mess by replacing the power strips with

12
00:00:36.919 --> 00:00:40.729
a centralised twelve-fold boss bar that was built right into the frame.

13
00:00:42.080 --> 00:00:45.840
This was fine for standard cloud surfers pulling 10 to 15 kilowatts.

14
00:00:46.540 --> 00:00:50.709
But today's IA clusters demand 100 kilowatts or more per rack.

15
00:00:51.680 --> 00:00:54.869
If you try to push that much power at 12 volts,

16
00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:56.459
your current goes through the roof.

17
00:00:56.720 --> 00:00:59.400
It goes way beyond simple power loss.

18
00:00:59.720 --> 00:01:03.779
Pushing that much current through a 12 volt bus bar would be catastrophic.

19
00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:05.000
It would melt the copper,

20
00:01:05.080 --> 00:01:06.360
sparks would fly

21
00:01:06.519 --> 00:01:08.900
and result in a complete system failure.

22
00:01:09.360 --> 00:01:09.769
So

23
00:01:10.040 --> 00:01:12.980
the rack and power project group changed the standard.

24
00:01:14.150 --> 00:01:18.370
ORV3 utilises a 48 volt DC buzz bar.

25
00:01:18.949 --> 00:01:20.379
By stepping up the voltage,

26
00:01:20.559 --> 00:01:23.160
we reduce the heat loss by 16 times.

27
00:01:24.620 --> 00:01:27.769
That means more power actually reaches the silicon

28
00:01:27.769 --> 00:01:29.849
instead of burning up in the infrastructure.

29
00:01:31.169 --> 00:01:33.879
We also totally reimagined power delivery.

30
00:01:36.010 --> 00:01:37.169
In a traditional setup,

31
00:01:37.290 --> 00:01:40.550
every single server has its own redundant power supply,

32
00:01:40.690 --> 00:01:42.449
which usually runs at a low,

33
00:01:42.569 --> 00:01:44.290
inefficient utilisation rate.

34
00:01:46.790 --> 00:01:48.000
ORV3 pulls that workload.

35
00:01:49.169 --> 00:01:52.809
It replaces dozens of individual power supplies with a

36
00:01:52.809 --> 00:01:56.709
single centralised power shelf loaded with modular rectifiers.

37
00:01:57.639 --> 00:02:01.639
By consolidating the AC to DC conversion for the entire wreck,

38
00:02:01.839 --> 00:02:03.620
we drive the utilisation rate up

39
00:02:03.800 --> 00:02:05.360
and the power losses down.

40
00:02:06.319 --> 00:02:09.279
This centralised approach simplifies deployment.

41
00:02:09.470 --> 00:02:14.080
IT gear slides in and connects to the power spine without any manual wiring.

42
00:02:14.869 --> 00:02:18.009
No thick power cords blocking your exhaust air flow.

43
00:02:19.020 --> 00:02:22.479
Eliminating server PSUs frees up motherboard space,

44
00:02:22.770 --> 00:02:24.350
enabling denser compute

45
00:02:24.539 --> 00:02:26.100
and improved system airflow.

46
00:02:27.600 --> 00:02:31.000
But delivering that much power creates two secondary challenges,

47
00:02:31.520 --> 00:02:33.320
extreme weight and extreme heat.

48
00:02:34.100 --> 00:02:37.259
The physical frame of the ORV3 rack has been reinforced

49
00:02:37.259 --> 00:02:40.479
to handle the massive weight of modern GPU chassis.

50
00:02:40.820 --> 00:02:41.889
More importantly,

51
00:02:42.139 --> 00:02:46.419
the ORV 3 frame futureproofs your data centre for the next generation of heat.

52
00:02:47.110 --> 00:02:49.550
It is designed to natively integrate liquid

53
00:02:49.550 --> 00:02:52.389
cooling manifolds right into the direct architecture.

54
00:02:53.220 --> 00:02:55.479
It introduces the Open Compute

55
00:02:55.660 --> 00:02:59.960
Universal Quick Disconnect Standard or UQD for short.

56
00:03:00.850 --> 00:03:04.300
ORV3 allows serving gear to be slid directly into the wreck,

57
00:03:04.529 --> 00:03:09.089
safely and seamlessly connecting its liquid cooling circuits without any drips.

58
00:03:10.360 --> 00:03:12.419
We solved the power delivery bottleneck,

59
00:03:12.720 --> 00:03:15.619
but extracting that heat is a whole different beast.

60
00:03:15.919 --> 00:03:19.240
Let's look at how we keep these wrecks from actually melting down.